The **Wronskian** of $n$ functions $y_1, y_2, \ldots, y_n$ (each at least $n-1$ times differentiable) is the determinant
\[
W[y_1, y_2, \ldots, y_n](t) = 
\begin{vmatrix}
y_1 & y_2 & \cdots & y_n \\
y_1' & y_2' & \cdots & y_n' \\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\
y_1^{(n-1)} & y_2^{(n-1)} & \cdots & y_n^{(n-1)}
\end{vmatrix}
\]

content.problem:
Find the Wronskian of $y_1 = e^t$, $y_2 = e^{2t}$, $y_3 = e^{3t}$.

**Solution.** We compute:
\[
W[e^t, e^{2t}, e^{3t}] = 
\begin{vmatrix}
e^t & e^{2t} & e^{3t} \\
e^t & 2e^{2t} & 3e^{3t} \\
e^t & 4e^{2t} & 9e^{3t}
\end{vmatrix}
\]

Factoring out $e^t$ from the first column, $e^{2t}$ from the second, and $e^{3t}$ from the third:
\[
W = e^t \cdot e^{2t} \cdot e^{3t} 
\begin{vmatrix}
1 & 1 & 1 \\
1 & 2 & 3 \\
1 & 4 & 9
\end{vmatrix}
= e^{6t}
\begin{vmatrix}
1 & 1 & 1 \\
1 & 2 & 3 \\
1 & 4 & 9
\end{vmatrix}
\]

Expanding the determinant (subtracting row 1 from rows 2 and 3 first):
\[
\begin{vmatrix}
1 & 1 & 1 \\
0 & 1 & 2 \\
0 & 3 & 8
\end{vmatrix}
= 1 \cdot (8 - 6) = 2
\]

Therefore, $W[e^t, e^{2t}, e^{3t}] = 2e^{6t} \neq 0$.
